<br>
First let me talk of what was meant -- that's more important than which words were used.  I think you start with the idea that that human intelligence is more interesting, exciting, fun, and in almost every way better than computer-controlled AI.  Well yes of course.  We all know humans are a lot more dynamic and interesting than machines -- humans have more 'spice'.  Yeah, we can all agree that a MMPG (or even a tabletop RPG that's not MM) where you face human-controlled opponents will be better than one that's completely automated.  But that's a long long way from arguing that the ability to kill the characters of the other people sitting around the table is what makes the game good.<br>
<br>
Now as to the idea that every game involves human opponents:<br>
What about those choose-an-adventure books, ie 'if you attack him, turn to page 153'?  Tada... a pen and paper RPG with just one human.  Sure they suck, but they're still pen and paper RPGs.  Now check out this argument: They suck because the AI is so simple.  And the AI is so simple because there's no human GM.  But I still think it's too much of a stretch to say they suck because there's no human GM.  Rather, I argue that the AI just needs a little improvement (well ok, a LOT of improvement, maybe even near-human-level intelligence).<br>
<br>
Now on to this idea that &quot;A GM and a player are not that different&quot;.  I'll refrain from laughing AT you, but from my point of view that's laughable.  In my view, the GM is the environment.  The GM decides whether it's raining or sunny, whether the hill is grassy or muddy or sandy or steep, whether that orc's friend heard the twang of your bowstring or didn't hear it at all, whether it takes 30 seconds to light your torch or fifteen minutes.  Everything from the earth to the moon and in between is supplied by and controlled by the GM.  Also a GM goes out of his way to give the players hints and characters to roleplay with and guide them toward interesting and appropriate adventures.  And when he controls those orcs and gnolls and whatever other opponents you face he's rooting for the players, hoping his guys get trounced... and most GMs will start cheating if necessary to make sure his guys lose.  This is all very different from how other players behave in a 'PvP' situation in a game like EQ.  In a PvP situation the other players do not have any more control over heavens and earth and everything else than you do, they aren't apt to give helpful hints and guidance leading up to your encounter, and they are not rooting for you to win.  For all these reasons, I believe PvP is very very different from what all pen and paper RPGs are based on.<br>
<br>
<br>
P.S.  I agree that a little PvP adds necessary spice to a game, and that human-controlled opponents are more fun than computer-controlled.  I agree that you have to take the griefers into account (presumably there should be some accountability, some significant consequences for being a murderer).  But I still think a D&amp;D game is a lot more like a blue EQ server, with the GM more like the server than another player.  If you really want an online game to be as dynamic as a tabletop game, try maintaining a 5 to 1 ratio of players to GMs.... now THAT just might do it.  Otherwise you'll just have to find good methods of running these games that do NOT emulate pen-and-paper RPGs. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/8/01 3:46:26 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> &quot;What about those choose-an-adventure books, ie 'if you attack him, turn to page 153'? Tada... a pen and paper RPG with just one human.&quot;<br>
<br>
