<br>
To the contrary, I would say from your description that it is you whose P&amp;P RPG experience has been somewhat shallow.  You appear to have GMs who woodenly played the NPCs.  You have my sympathies.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;3) A DM/GM is a Referee.. If he is siding with the players it is a Monty Haul and booring.. If he sides against the players it is a no win situation and agrivating... Either way, you have a dead game which people will not come back to play. <br>
<br>
You seem to missing something here...namely, a side.  WHO is the &quot;side&quot; against the players?  More importantly, WHO is controlling that side?<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;You set up dungeons/adventures of an appropriate level and keep all dice rolls public.. Flukes in dice rolls can make the game exciting but even if the players characters die it is fair. <br>
<br>
Apparently, you think the other side are the monsters/NPCs encountered, correct?  And who is controlling them?  A human.  That's my point.<br>
<br>
It doesn't matter if the human doing the controlling is doing a good job or a bad job.  It's still a human doing the controlling.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;4) If you want to have monsters with character have a second referee (or someone who's character(s) has died) play the part of the monster. This adds another demension to the game and is more of a true PvP but one where monsters will run and get help or sneak up on players. <br>
<br>
And if that second referee is not available, WHO IS PLAYING THE PART OF THE MONSTER?  The GM, of course.  All GMs I have ever met have been human.  Thank you for proving my point.<br>
<br>
Moreover, this is the basis for my first comment.  If your GM never had the monsters run and get help, or try to sneak up on you, you had a weak GM. You don't need a second GM, you just need a good GM in the first place.<br>
<br>
<br>
Your other points go to the issue of how to incorporate the HvH element back into a MMORPG, and thus are getting beyond the scope of this little thread.  My point is simply to get people who have a knee-jerk reaction against the term &quot;PvP&quot; to realize that &quot;PvP&quot; really is &quot;HvH&quot; (Human vs. Human), and that HvH is at the core of P&amp;P RPGs.  <br>
<br>
Human conflict (HvH) is also at the core of the nearly every good story ever told in any media, but that's a different thread...:) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usaphyrreeq.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saphyrre EQ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/9/01 6:55:41 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> The one thing you have to keep in mind here, is that NO MMORPG will EVER be like a PnP RPG. The reason? The players. <br>
<br>
This has been said before, but I think overlooked in all these discussions. In a PnP RPG, you have real accountability for actions. I don't think you are ever going to see one member of a gaming group bring in his level 15 magic user to jump from behind a tree and kill off the rest of the group, who are all using their level 3-4 characters. If he did, he obviously wouldn't be invited back to the next session, and might even be asked to leave immediately. In fact, most DMs would allow the players ot keep their chars, saying that the incident never happened. The result? An hour or so of wasted time, and one person loses his gaming group. Now, take the same thing in an MMORPG, such as EQ. Some rules prevent a much higher level player from killing lower levels, but the same idea is in place. A higher level character ganks a bunch of low levels. Net result? Depending on the rules of that particular game, maybe loss of all items and some XP (or skill points, whatever), maybe a long corpse run for some of them, things like that. In general, just plain aggravation for people who have done nothing but stroll into the line of sight of a moron. What happens to the murderer? Usually nothing. If there are stringent consequences, such as being flagged a certain way where all the guards will KOS you, such as UO, then all they have to do is use a second account to do their normal interactions, and use that one char as their ganker. Hell, even their close friends might not know who their other char is. No matter what the &quot;consequences&quot; enforced bythe game, there are always ways around them, so in fact, there ARE NO consequences, and NO accountability. It is impossible to make it so that there are. <br>
<br>
It is impossible to get rid of &quot;grief&quot; players in a MMORPG. Because of this, it is impossible to have any kind of PvP environment that most people will enjoy. I LIKE EQ's approach. They have realized this, and simply taken PvP out of the equation. Then they made other servers to accomodate those who just couldn't live without it. I like that, because it gets all the gankers together, where they can gank each other, and I never have to deal with them at all. I don't mean to say that EVERYONE who plays on a PvP server is a grief player, but you will have to admit that the lion's share of them are, simply because they CAN'T gank people on blue servers, so they HAVE to play on the red ones. <br>
<br>
<br>
About the distinction between PvP and PvE: Many have brought up that DM vs Players is really PvP, because the DM is human, too. While that is technically true, you also must make a distinction between players and DM, even though they are all human. They play the game by different sets of rules, and for different purposes. The player play with the goal of slaying the dragon, or rescuing the princess, or some such. The DM plays with the goal of making everything work so that the players have a challenging yet accomplishable  mission. A DM has had a good game when the players succesfully &quot;win&quot; their dungeon, but just barely. You can't just lump DMs and players together into the same category simply because they are both human controlled. Even in spite of that, they are very different in terms of actual game play. Therefore, when I speak of &quot;PvP&quot; I am talking about the players that control characters (which they have been leveling, equiping, and grooming, much as Korwin pointed out) fighting and killing each other, not the players fighting alongside each other to kill human-controlled monsters the DM &quot;rolled up&quot; on the spot. There IS a difference between a level 8 cleric that's been carefully groomed over the last 4 months and a pack of hobgoblins that the DM just rolled up their hitpoints, gave a few items, and sent into battle. <br>
<br>
True, D&amp;D has the posibility of PvP. However, I have never seen it in any of my games, and I'd be willing to bet that most others haven't either. Unless and until a software company can come up with a way to duplicate the nature of D&amp;D's PvP system (i.e. it's possible for one player to kill another, but it rarely if ever happens), then I will stick with games that have no PvP, or have the option to avoid it entirely without missing any of the PvE game. I just don't think it's possible, because of something that the software developers can't control: the nature of some of the players.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usylphan2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sylphan2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/9/01 8:04:07 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> &lt;&lt;&lt;GM/DM-&gt;species = Human<br>
Player_in_PvP_conflict-&gt;species = Human<br>
Every_mob_you_fight_in_EQ-&gt;species = Computer<br>
<br>
Human = Human<br>
Human &lt;&gt; Computer&gt;&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
Wow, what a leap of logic.  So I guess all humans are equal?  Grief player = Roleplayer?  I'm afraid that drawing little arrows does not make your argument sound.  You might as well have written<br>
<br>
