Xegony</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/9/01 10:56:11 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: wit nit</span><hr size=1> &quot;P&amp;P human vs human is not adversarial.&quot;<br>
<br>
It is adversarial.  But not griefer-style. <br>
<br>
The GM takes the role of different adversary (or adversaries) through the game.  This provides the conflict that is present in most stories.  It not only helps the story flow, it CREATES the story.<br>
<br>
We are in agreement that the HvH element in P&amp;P RPGs usually works well, I believe.  And that the HvH element in MMORPGs often does not.<br>
<br>
I previously said that &quot;accountability&quot; was one key element to the success of HvH.  As you note, if you have a sadistic GM, then you have a &quot;griefer.&quot;  In the P&amp;P RPG world, people just stop playing if that person is a GM.  That GM suffers appropriate consequences as a result of his or her actions.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=badaf>Badaf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/10/01 6:03:49 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ah!</span><hr size=1> To me, Player vs Player has always been about equality. Meaning playing on a level playing field, where each player plays by the same rules. And on this level playing field, one player pits his skills against the other in order to obtain a goal that only one of them can obtain. Chess, football, Quake Deathmatch, etc. <br>
<br>
PnP AD&amp;D, in relation to DMs and Players, does not fall into this catagory. DMs do not follow the rules, they make them and break them in order to provide a fun adventure for the players. <br>
<br>
If football allowed for one side to freely adjust the scoreboard in order for the other team experience a close game that they eventually would win, i wouldnt consider it Player vs Player any longer. Would you? Sure, yould could isolate a given play, and point out that that defensive player stopped that offensive player, therefore its PvP. But in the context of the entire game its not. <br>
<br>
DMs and Players play by different rules and have different goals. To me, this totally destroys any notion that the interaction between these 2 is PvP. While a DM might step into a role whose purpose is to enter into combat with the Players, his goal is not the same as the players nor are the rules he follows. <br>
<br>
Also, i would like to point out that even computer AI can simulate some NPCs equal to a human controlled AI. Low level undead, for example, attack the nearest creature without regard to life or limb. Easy for a computer to handle that. <br>
<br>
Anyways, it all boils down to Player-versus-Player not having a concrete definition. Therefore its open to interpretation. While you can argue what it means to you, it does not mean that you are correct. <br>
<br>
Its my opinion that D&amp;D was not &quot;based&quot; on PvP in any way, shape, or form.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/10/01 6:32:15 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ah!</span><hr size=1> &quot;Equality&quot; in PvP or any game with HvH is a myth.  <br>
<br>
The &quot;level playing field&quot; is a myth as well.<br>
<br>
<br>
First, there is the obvious truth that the humans involved are not equal.  Some have faster reflexes.  Some are stronger.  Some are more flexible.  Some are more intelligent.  Some have more practice.  Some have better equipment or training. Some have more knowledge of the particular game.  These differences apply to any game, anywhere. <br>
<br>
In fact, I daresay that it is these differences that make the game worthwhile.  To play and to watch. <br>
<br>
Second, there are additional technological differences particular to online computer games.  One player has a cable modem, another is still using their telephone line.  One has a top of the line computer with a fast video card and lots of memory, other still are clunking around with PIIIs and voodoo 2s (or older, god forbid).  Even with the exact same equipment set-up, geographical differences can make a huge difference in the quality and speed of their connection.   <br>
<br>
Fantasize all you want.  Ain't no such thing as a &quot;level playing field&quot; in an online game.  None of the games you listed have a truly level playing field, especially Quake.  Chess, perhaps, comes closest, but even there there is a difference: white goes first and has a slight advantage thereby.  <br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Its my opinion that D&amp;D was not &quot;based&quot; on PvP in any way, shape, or form.<br>
<br>
Then you must have been playing with yourself....:)<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/10/01 6:51:28 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/rtfm.gif width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ah!</span><hr size=1> Scirocco says:  <b><i>The "level playing field" is a myth as well.</b></i><br>
<br>
Actually, it's not.  A level <b>playing field</b> does not equate to equal skills, but rather to equal opportunity.  If went in a 1 on 1 game of basketball with a pro, I would lose horribly because of the differences in physical makeup, skills, and experience -- but the playing field would certainly be equal.<br>
<br>
PvP <b>is</b> about a level playing field, and that is what makes it fun.  Sure, differences in experience, reaction time, and quality of internet connection will affect performance, but each player is subject to the same rules established by the game server.  In some games (HLCS, Q3, and the like), the whole aspect of character development is removed entirely just to make the characters even more equal, in turn making PvP more fun, because it becomes more of a test of l337 fragging skillz.<br>
<br>
Of course, none of this has ANYTHING to do with the original topic (which so few readers have been able to grasp), and you're going to likely to confuse them even more now.  :D<font size=0> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0> at: 7/10/01 6:53:09 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/10/01 6:58:44 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ah!</span><hr size=1> If you place all of the different factors that vary from player to player (such as connection speed, who goes first, etc.) into the &quot;player differences&quot; category, thus removing them from the definition of what constitutes the &quot;playing field,&quot; then yes, I'll agree that you can have a level playing field.<br>
<br>
BTW, being governed by the same set of game rules does not necessarily mean being treated the same under those rules.  <br>
