 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon2.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umeddik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Meddik</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://aodoctors.homestead.com/files/cross.jpg BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/10/01 7:49:18 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ah!</span><hr size=1> (Note: When I reference PvP here, I'm not really speaking of Scirroco's concept of GM as PvP, but more the Commonly accepted definition, of a normal player who can attack other normal players.)<br>
<br>
I don't mind PvP, so long as there is a way to opt out, without missing a Huge part of the PvE environment of a game.<br>
<br>
I know, for realism, RP, competitiveness, whatever, PvP needs to be an option. There are many people who will not be happy unless they can engage in PvP.<br>
<br>
However, on the other hand, there are those such as myself that really have absolutely no interest in PvP. We will not be happy if we are forced into PvP, or if we will miss large portions of the PvE game by avoiding PvP.<br>
<br>
Its a fairly tough dilemma.<br>
<br>
Those in the PvP side of the equation, I have heard many say that a non-PvP game is no fun to them. Some also claim that they should be rewarded more for being in a PvP area, due to risk/reward.<br>
<br>
My 2 cents: If PvP is more fun to you, then you already have the reward you deserve from the additional risk you are in. I don't think that anyone should recieve more XP, Loot, or anything else of that nature because they are willing to engage in PvP. A Title, or a ranking of some sort, fine. But nothing that would have any influence in the PvE system.<br>
<br>
As for myself, I feel that EQ had a decent approach, except that it was impossible to switch from PvP to PvE areas. AO seems to have a good idea, although Nobody knows how the little details will work yet. UO? Well, I quit UO the day EQ was released. Back then, it had a horrid PvP system. In fact, were it not for that game and its flawed initial implementation of PvP, there would likely be many many more gamers willing to give PvP a second chance. <p><center><B>Meddik,</B> Rebel Doctor
